<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-title">Anchor question</div>
  What does Chennai do about climate change — and what does the science say is worth doing?
</div>

<div class="prose">
  <p>Unit 4 explicitly launches <strong>Thread 4 — Climate Action</strong> as the unit's central thread. The audience is the same one you wrote for in <a href="/units/unit-2/">Unit 2</a> — a hypothetical Greater Chennai Corporation planning meeting. The format is harder (≤4-page <em>policy brief</em>, not landscape reading) and the defense is longer (4-minute pitch + 3-minute panel Q&amp;A, vs. U2's 3 + 2). The science is also more abstract — you'll work with IPCC AR6 projections, SSP scenarios, climate-model outputs, and tipping-point feedbacks before the unit lets you write recommendations.</p>
  <p><strong>How we frame this content matters.</strong> Climate is heavy. The unit's posture is <em>"this is a challenge we engage with"</em> — agency mode, not doom narrative. Students personally affected by Chennai's 2015 floods, ongoing air quality, dengue, or relatives in flood-vulnerable wards may opt out of specific adaptation challenges and into others without penalty or explanation needed. The 8 challenge cards are designed so every student can find one they can engage with from a position of agency rather than helplessness.</p>
  <p>The summative — the <a href="/units/unit-4/assessment-chennai-climate-brief/">Chennai Climate Brief</a> — is the third major Brief-shaped deliverable of the year (after the U0 Source Dossier and the U2 Landscape Reading). The Policy Panel defense in Block 12 is the third defense in the year-long defense arc. The audience-awareness muscle you built in U2 carries over here — and stretches further.</p>
</div>

<section aria-label="Unit 4 blocks" style="margin-top: 24px;">
  <h2 style="font-size: 22px; color: var(--ink); margin-bottom: 12px;">The twelve blocks</h2>
  <div class="section-grid">
    <a class="section-card" href="/units/unit-4/block-1/">
      <div class="card-title">Block 1 — The Greenhouse Effect</div>
      <div class="card-desc">Energy-balance diagrams. Distinguish water-vapor feedbacks from CO₂ forcing. Why Earth without an atmosphere would be ~-18°C.</div>
    </a>
    <a class="section-card" href="/units/unit-4/block-2/">
      <div class="card-title">Block 2 — Energy Balance: The Math</div>
      <div class="card-desc">Calculate planetary temperature under different greenhouse-gas concentrations using quantitative energy-balance equations.</div>
    </a>
    <a class="section-card" href="/units/unit-4/block-3/">
      <div class="card-title">Block 3 — The Carbon Cycle</div>
      <div class="card-desc">Major reservoirs and fluxes. Distinguish fast (photosynthesis-respiration) vs. slow (weathering-sedimentation) pathways.</div>
    </a>
    <a class="section-card" href="/units/unit-4/block-4/">
      <div class="card-title">Block 4 — Human Acceleration + Warming Signal</div>
      <div class="card-desc">Anthropogenic perturbations. Read the Keeling curve + 1850-present temperature record. Attribution to greenhouse forcing.</div>
    </a>
    <a class="section-card" href="/units/unit-4/block-5/">
      <div class="card-title">Block 5 — IPCC AR6 + Brief Assigned</div>
      <div class="card-desc">OPVL on AR6 Summary for Policymakers figures. SSP scenarios + confidence levels. Climate Brief assigned today; 8 adaptation challenges released.</div>
    </a>
    <a class="section-card" href="/units/unit-4/block-6/">
      <div class="card-title">Block 6 — Climate Models</div>
      <div class="card-desc">How they work, how they're wrong, how to read them. Decode IPCC projection figures. What models include vs. don't. Projection vs. prediction.</div>
    </a>
    <a class="section-card" href="/units/unit-4/block-7/">
      <div class="card-title">Block 7 — Regional Climate + Lock Challenge</div>
      <div class="card-desc">From global average to Chennai's monsoon. IPCC regional chapters + GCC Climate Action Plan. Adaptation challenge locked today.</div>
    </a>
    <a class="section-card" href="/units/unit-4/block-8/">
      <div class="card-title">Block 8 — Tipping Points + Feedbacks</div>
      <div class="card-desc">Ice-albedo, water-vapor, permafrost-methane, AMOC slowdown. Connects to Unit 1 feedback-loop muscle.</div>
    </a>
    <a class="section-card" href="/units/unit-4/block-9/">
      <div class="card-title">Block 9 — Adaptation vs. Mitigation</div>
      <div class="card-desc">Mitigation = reduce the cause. Adaptation = reduce the impact. Draft Recommendations focused on actionable GCC interventions.</div>
    </a>
    <a class="section-card" href="/units/unit-4/block-10/">
      <div class="card-title">Block 10 — Brief Work Day + Peer Feedback</div>
      <div class="card-desc">Worked-example Brief modeled. Structured peer feedback on policy language + audience awareness + recommendation concreteness.</div>
    </a>
    <a class="section-card" href="/units/unit-4/block-11/">
      <div class="card-title">Block 11 — Final Drafting + Panel Rehearsal</div>
      <div class="card-desc">Finalize the Brief. Rehearse the 4-min pitch + panel-question responses in pairs or trios. Format choice locked.</div>
    </a>
    <a class="section-card" href="/units/unit-4/block-12/">
      <div class="card-title">Block 12 — Policy Panel Q&A</div>
      <div class="card-desc">Briefs submitted. 4-min pitch + 3-min panel Q&A, peers as Greater Chennai Corporation officials. Unit-close reflection.</div>
    </a>
  </div>
</section>

